<div id=3D"What-is-Probability?">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>What is Probability?</h2>
</div>
<p><strong>Probability</strong> can be defined as the ratio of the number o=
f favorable outcomes to the total number of outcomes of an event. For an ex=
periment having 'n' number of outcomes, the number of favorable outcomes ca=
n be denoted by x. The formula to calculate the probability of an event is =
as follows.</p>
<p>Probability(Event) =3D Favorable Outcomes/Total Outcomes =3D x/n</p>
<p>Probability is used to predict the outcomes for the tossing of coins, ro=
lling of dice, or drawing a card from a pack of playing cards. The probabil=
ity is classified into two types:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/theoretical-probability/">Theor=
etical probability</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/experimental-probability/">Expe=
rimental probability</a></li>
</ul>
<p>To understand each of these types, click on the respective links.</p>
<div id=3D"Terms-in-Probability">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Terminology of Probability Theory</h2>
</div>
<p>The following <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/terms-of-probabili=
ty/">terms</a> in <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/probability-theor=
y/">probability theorey</a> help in a better understanding of the concepts =
of probability.</p>
<p><strong>Experiment:</strong> A trial or an operation conducted to produc=
e an outcome is called an experiment.</p>
<p><strong>Sample Space: </strong>All the possible outcomes of an experimen=
t together constitute a <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/sample-spac=
e/">sample space</a>. For example, the sample space of tossing a coin is {h=
ead, tail}.</p>
<p><strong>Favorable Outcome:</strong> An event that has produced the desir=
ed result or expected event is called a favorable outcome. For example, whe=
n we roll two dice, the possible/favorable outcomes of getting the sum of n=
umbers on the two dice as 4 are (1,3), (2,2), and (3,1).</p>
<p><strong>Trial:</strong> A trial denotes doing a random experiment.</p>
<p><b>Random Experiment:</b> An experiment that has a well-defined set of o=
utcomes is called a <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/random-experime=
nts/">random experiment</a>. For example, when we toss a coin, we know that=
 we would get ahead or tail, but we are not sure which one will appear.</p>
<p><b>Event: </b>The total number of outcomes of a random experiment is cal=
led an <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/events-in-probability/">even=
t</a>.</p>
<p><b>Equally Likely Events:</b> Events that have the same chances or proba=
bility of occurring are called equally likely events. The outcome of one ev=
ent is independent of the other. For example, when we toss a coin, there ar=
e equal chances of getting a head or a tail.</p>
<p><strong>Exhaustive Events:</strong> When the set of all outcomes of an e=
vent is equal to the sample space, we call it an <a href=3D"https://www.cue=
math.com/data/exhaustive-events/">exhaustive event</a>.</p>
<p><b>Mutually Exclusive Events:</b> Events that cannot happen simultaneous=
ly are called <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/mutually-exclusive-ev=
ents/">mutually exclusive events</a>. For example, the climate can be eithe=
r hot or cold. We cannot experience the same weather simultaneously.</p>
<div id=3D"events">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Events in Probability</h2>
</div>
<p>In probability theory, an event is a set of outcomes of an experiment or=
 a subset of the sample space. If P(E) represents the probability of an eve=
nt E, then, we have,</p>
<ul>
<li>P(E) =3D 0 if and only if E is an impossible event.</li>
<li>P(E) =3D 1 if and only if E is a certain event.</li>
<li>0 =E2=89=A4 P(E) =E2=89=A4 1.</li>
</ul>
<p>Suppose, we are given two events, "A" and "B", then the probability of e=
vent A, P(A) &gt; P(B) if and only if event "A" is more likely to occur tha=
n the event "B". Sample space(S) is the set of all of the possible outcomes=
 of an experiment and n(S) represents the number of outcomes in the sample =
space.</p>
<p>P(E) =3D n(E)/n(S)</p>
<p>P(E=E2=80=99) =3D (n(S) - n(E))/n(S) =3D 1 - (n(E)/n(S))</p>
<p>E=E2=80=99 represents that the event will not occur.</p>
<p>Therefore, now we can also conclude that, P(E) + P(E=E2=80=99) =3D 1</p>
<div id=3D"formula">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Probability Formula</h2>
</div>
<p>The probability equation defines the likelihood of the happening of an e=
vent. It is the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/commercial-math/ratio/">=
ratio</a> of favorable outcomes to the total favorable outcomes. The <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/probability-rules/">probability formula</=
a> can be expressed as,</p>
<p><img alt=3D"probability formula says p of a equals number of favorable o=
utcomes over total number of outcomes." src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9iqe.cloud=
front.net/media/seo_landing_files/probability-formula-1-1634878086.png" sty=
le=3D"width: 500px;"></p>
<p>i.e., P(A) =3D n(A)/n(S)</p>
<p>where,</p>
<ul>
<li>P(A) is the probability of an event 'B'.</li>
<li>n(A) is the number of favorable outcomes of an event 'B'.</li>
<li>n(S) is the total number of events occurring in a sample space.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Different Probability Formulas</h3>
<p><strong>Probability formula with <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/prob=
ability-a-union-b-formula/">addition rule</a>: </strong> Whenever an event =
is the union of two other events, say A and B, then<br>
P(A or B) =3D P(A) + P(B) - P(A=E2=88=A9B)<br>
P(A =E2=88=AA B) =3D P(A) + P(B) - P(A=E2=88=A9B)</p>
<p><strong>Probability formula with the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/=
data/complementary-events/">complementary</a> rule: </strong>Whenever an ev=
ent is the complement of another event, specifically, if A is an event, the=
n P(not A) =3D 1 - P(A) or P(A') =3D 1 - P(A).<br>
P(A) + P(A=E2=80=B2) =3D 1.</p>
<p><strong>Probability formula with the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/=
conditional-probability-formula/">conditional rule</a></strong>: When event=
 A is already known to have occurred, the probability of event B is known a=
s conditional probability and is given by:<br>
P(B=E2=88=A3A) =3D P(A=E2=88=A9B)/P(A)</p>
<p><strong>Probability formula with <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data=
/multiplication-rule-of-probability/">multiplication rule</a></strong>: Whe=
never an event is the intersection of two other events, that is, events A a=
nd B need to occur simultaneously. Then</p>
<ul>
<li>P(A =E2=88=A9 B) =3D P(A)=E2=8B=85P(B) (in case of <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.cuemath.com/data/independent-events/">independent events</a>)</li>
<li>P(A=E2=88=A9B) =3D P(A)=E2=8B=85P(B=E2=88=A3A) (in case of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.cuemath.com/data/dependent-events/">dependent events</a>)</li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"calculate">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Calculating Probability</h2>
<p>In an experiment, the probability of an event is the possibility of that=
 event occurring. The probability of any event is a value between (and incl=
uding) "0" and "1". Follow the steps below for calculating probability of a=
n event A:</p>
</div>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 1: </strong>Find the sample space of the experiment and co=
unt the elements. Denote it by n(S).</li>
<li><strong>Step 2: </strong>Find the number of favorable outcomes and deno=
te it by n(A).</li>
<li><strong>Step 3: </strong>To find probability, divide n(A) by n(S). i.e.=
, P(A) =3D n(A)/n(S).</li>
</ul>
<p>Here are some examples that well describe the process of finding probabi=
lity.</p>
<p><strong>Example 1</strong>: Find the probability of getting a number les=
s than 5 when a dice is rolled by using the probability formula.</p>
<p><strong>Solution </strong></p>
<p>To find:<br>
Probability of getting a number less than 5<br>
Given: Sample space, S =3D {1,2,3,4,5,6}<br>
Therefore, n(S) =3D 6</p>
<p>Let A be the event of getting a number less than 5. Then A =3D {1,2,3,4}=
<br>
So, n(A) =3D 4</p>
<p>Using the probability equation,<br>
P(A) =3D (n(A))/(n(s))<br>
p(A) =3D 4/6<br>
m =3D 2/3</p>
<p><strong>Answer: </strong>The probability of getting a number less than 5=
 is 2/3.</p>
<p><strong>Example 2:</strong> What is the probability of getting a sum of =
9 when two dice are thrown?</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>There is a total of 36 possibilities when we throw two dice.<br>
To get the desired outcome i.e., 9, we can have the following favorable out=
comes.<br>
(4,5),(5,4),(6,3)(3,6). There are 4 favorable outcomes.<br>
Probability of an event P(E) =3D (Number of favorable outcomes) =C3=B7 (Tot=
al outcomes in a sample space)<br>
Probability of getting number 9 =3D 4 =C3=B7 36 =3D 1/9</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Therefore the probability of getting a sum of 9=
 is 1/9.</p>
<div id=3D"tree">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Probability Tree Diagram</h2>
</div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/probability-tree-diagram/">tre=
e diagram</a> in probability is a visual representation that helps in findi=
ng the possible outcomes or the probability of any event occurring or not o=
ccurring. The tree diagram for the toss of a coin given below helps in unde=
rstanding the possible outcomes when a coin is tossed. Each branch of the t=
ree is associated with the respective probability (just like how 0.5 is wri=
tten on each brack in the figure below). Remember that the sum of probabili=
ties of all branches that start from the same point is always 1 (here, 0.5 =
+ 0.5 =3D 1).</p>
<p><img alt=3D"probability tree diagram when a coin is tossed has two outco=
mes head and tail each with probability of 0 point 5" src=3D"https://d138zd=
1ktt9iqe.cloudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/tree-diagram-probability-16=
34616751.png" style=3D"width: 400px;"></p>
<div id=3D"type">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Types of Probability</h2>
</div>
<p>There can be different perspectives or types of probabilities based on t=
he nature of the outcome or the approach followed while finding probability=
 of an event happening. The four types of probabilities are,</p>
<ul>
<li>Classical Probability</li>
<li>Empirical Probability</li>
<li>Subjective Probability</li>
<li>Axiomatic Probability</li>
</ul>
<h3>Classical Probability</h3>
<p>Classical probability, often referred to as the "priori" or "theoretical=
 probability", states that in an experiment where there are B equally likel=
y outcomes, and event X has exactly A of these outcomes, then the probabili=
ty of X is A/B, or P(X) =3D A/B. For example, when a fair die is rolled, th=
ere are six possible outcomes that are equally likely. That means, there is=
 a 1/6 probability of rolling each number on the die.</p>
<h3>Empirical Probability</h3>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/empirical-probability-formula/">e=
mpirical probability</a> or the experimental perspective evaluates probabil=
ity through thought experiments. For example, if a weighted die is rolled, =
such that we don't know which side has the weight, then we can get an idea =
for the probability of each outcome by rolling the die number of times and =
calculating the proportion of times the die gives that outcome and thus fin=
d the probability of that outcome.</p>
<h3>Subjective Probability</h3>
<p>Subjective probability considers an individual's own belief of an event =
occurring. For example, the probability of a particular team winning a foot=
ball match on a fan's opinion is more dependent upon their own belief and f=
eeling and not on a formal mathematical calculation.</p>
<h3>Axiomatic Probability</h3>
<p>In axiomatic probability, a set of rules or axioms by Kolmogorov are app=
lied to all the types. The chances of occurrence or non-occurrence of any e=
vent can be quantified by the applications of these axioms, given as,</p>
<ul>
<li>The smallest possible probability is zero, and the largest is one.</li>
<li>An event that is certain has a probability equal to one.</li>
<li>Any two mutually exclusive events cannot occur simultaneously, while th=
e union of events says only one of them can occur.</li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"Probability-Tossing-a-Coin">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Coin Toss Probability</h2>
</div>
<p>Let us now look into the probability of <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.c=
om/data/tossing-a-coin/">tossing a coin</a>. Quite often in games like cric=
ket, for making a decision as to who would bowl or bat first, we sometimes =
use the tossing of a coin and decide based on the outcome of the toss. Let =
us check how we can use the concept of probability in the tossing of a sing=
le coin. Further, we shall also look into the tossing of two and three coin=
s.</p>
<h3>Tossing a Coin</h3>
<p>A single coin on tossing has two outcomes, a head, and a tail. The conce=
pt of probability which is the ratio of favorable outcomes to the total num=
ber of outcomes can be used in finding probability of getting the head and =
the probability of getting a tail.</p>
<p>Total number of possible outcomes =3D 2; Sample Space =3D {H, T}; H: Hea=
d, T: Tail</p>
<ul>
<li>P(H) =3D Number of heads/Total outcomes =3D 1/2</li>
<li>P(T)=3D Number of Tails/ Total outcomes =3D 1/2</li>
</ul>
<h3>Tossing Two Coins</h3>
<p>In the process of tossing two coins, we have a total of four (=3D 2<sup>=
2</sup>) outcomes. The probability formula can be used to find the probabil=
ity of two heads, one head, no head, and a similar probability can be calcu=
lated for the number of tails. The probability calculations for the two hea=
ds are as follows.</p>
<p>Total number of outcomes =3D 4; Sample Space =3D {(H, H), (H, T), (T, H)=
, (T, T)}</p>
<ul>
<li>P(2H) =3D P(0 T) =3D Number of outcome with two heads/Total Outcomes =
=3D 1/4</li>
<li>P(1H) =3D P(1T) =3D Number of outcomes with only one head/Total Outcome=
s =3D 2/4 =3D 1/2</li>
<li>P(0H) =3D (2T) =3D Number of outcome with two heads/Total Outcomes =3D =
1/4</li>
</ul>
<h3>Tossing Three Coins</h3>
<p>The number of total outcomes on tossing three coins simultaneously is eq=
ual to 2<sup>3</sup> =3D 8. For these outcomes, we can find the probability=
 of getting one head, two heads, three heads, and no head. A similar probab=
ility can also be calculated for the number of tails.</p>
<p>Total number of outcomes =3D 2<sup>3</sup> =3D 8 Sample Space =3D {(H, H=
, H), (H, H, T), (H, T, H), (T, H, H), (T, T, H), (T, H, T), (H, T, T), (T,=
 T, T)}</p>
<ul>
<li>P(0H) =3D P(3T) =3D Number of outcomes with no heads/Total Outcomes =3D=
 1/8</li>
<li>P(1H) =3D P(2T) =3D Number of Outcomes with one head/Total Outcomes =3D=
 3/8</li>
<li>P(2H) =3D P(1T) =3D Number of outcomes with two heads /Total Outcomes =
=3D 3/8</li>
<li>P(3H) =3D P(0T) =3D Number of outcomes with three heads/Total Outcomes =
=3D 1/8</li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"Probability-Rolling-a-Dice">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Dice Roll Probability</h2>
</div>
<p>Many games use dice to decide the moves of players across the games. A d=
ice has six possible outcomes and the outcomes of a dice is a game of chanc=
e and can be obtained by using the concepts of probability. Some games also=
 use two dice, and there are numerous probabilities that can be calculated =
for outcomes using two dice. Let us now check the outcomes, their probabili=
ties for one dice and two dice respectively.</p>
<h3>Rolling One Dice</h3>
<p>The total number of outcomes on <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/=
rolling-a-die/">rolling a die</a> is 6, and the sample space is {1, 2, 3, 4=
, 5, 6}. Here we shall compute the following few probabilities to help in b=
etter understanding the concept of probability on rolling one dice.</p>
<ul>
<li>P(<a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/numbers/even-numbers/">Even Number=
</a>) =3D Number of even number outcomes/Total Outcomes =3D 3/6 =3D 1/2</li=
>
<li>P(<a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/numbers/odd-numbers/">Odd Number</=
a>) =3D Number of odd number outcomes/Total Outcomes =3D 3/6 =3D 1/2</li>
<li>P(<a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/numbers/prime-numbers/">Prime Numb=
er</a>) =3D Number of prime number outcomes/Total Outcomes =3D 3/6 =3D 1/2<=
/li>
</ul>
<h3>Rolling Two Dice</h3>
<p>The total number of outcomes on rolling two dice is 6<sup>2</sup> =3D 36=
. The following image shows the sample space of 36 outcomes on rolling two =
dice.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Sample Space of Outcomes of Two Dice helps in finding Probab=
ilities and it has 36 elements" src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9iqe.cloudfront.ne=
t/media/seo_landing_files/sample-space-in-probability-1634616693.png" style=
=3D"width: 450px;"></p>
<p>Let us check a few probabilities of the outcomes from two dice. The prob=
abilities are as follows.</p>
<ul>
<li>Probability of getting a doublet(Same number) =3D 6/36 =3D 1/6</li>
<li>Probability of getting a number 3 on at least one dice =3D 11/36</li>
<li>Probability of getting a sum of 7 =3D 6/36 =3D 1/6</li>
</ul>
<p>As we see, when we roll a single die, there are 6 possibilities. When we=
 roll two dice, there are 36 (=3D 6<sup>2</sup>) possibilities. When we rol=
l 3 dice we get 216 (=3D 6<sup>3</sup>) possibilities. So a general formula=
 to represent the number of outcomes on rolling 'n' dice is 6<sup>n</sup>.<=
/p>
<div id=3D"Probability-of-Drawing-Cards">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Probability of Drawing Cards</h2>
</div>
<p>A deck containing 52 cards is grouped into four suits of clubs, diamonds=
, hearts, and spades. Each of the clubs, diamonds, hearts, and spades have =
13 cards each, which sum up to 52. Now let us discuss the probability of dr=
awing cards from a pack. The symbols on the cards are shown below. Spades a=
nd clubs are black cards. Hearts and diamonds are red cards.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Sample Space of deck of cards contains 52 cards out of which=
 26 are black and 26 are red." src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9iqe.cloudfront.net=
/media/seo_landing_files/probability-02-1623664728.png" style=3D"width: 450=
px;"></p>
<p>The 13 cards in each suit are ace, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, jack, que=
en, king. In these, the jack, the queen, and the king are called face cards=
. We can understand the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/card-probab=
ility/">card probability</a> from the following examples.</p>
<ul>
<li>The probability of drawing a black card is P(Black card) =3D 26/52 =3D =
1/2</li>
<li>The probability of drawing a hearts card is P(Hearts) =3D 13/52 =3D 1/4=
</li>
<li>The probability of drawing a face card is P(Face card) =3D 12/52 =3D 3/=
13</li>
<li>The probability of drawing a card numbered 4 is P(4) =3D 4/52 =3D 1/13<=
/li>
<li>The probability of drawing a red card numbered 4 is P(4 Red) =3D 2/52 =
=3D 1/26</li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"Basic-Theorems-on-Probability">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Probability Theorems</h2>
</div>
<p>The following theorems of probability are helpful to understand the appl=
ications of probability and also perform the numerous calculations involvin=
g probability.</p>
<p><strong>Theorem 1: </strong>The sum of the probability of happening of a=
n event and not happening of an event is equal to 1. P(A) + P(A') =3D 1.</p=
>
<p><strong>Theorem 2:</strong> The probability of an impossible event or th=
e probability of an event not happening is always equal to 0. P(=CF=95) =3D=
 0.</p>
<p><strong>Theorem 3:</strong> The probability of a sure event is always eq=
ual to 1. P(A) =3D 1</p>
<p><strong>Theorem 4:</strong> The probability of happening of any event al=
ways lies between 0 and 1. 0 <u>&lt;</u> P(A) <u>&lt;</u> 1</p>
<p><strong>Theorem 5:</strong> If there are two events A and B, we can appl=
y the formula of the union of two sets and we can derive the formula for th=
e probability of happening of event A or event B as follows.</p>
<p>P(A=E2=88=AAB) =3D P(A) + P(B) - P(A=E2=88=A9B)</p>
<p>Also for two mutually exclusive events A and B, we have P( A U B) =3D P(=
A) + P(B)</p>
<h3>Bayes' Theorem on Conditional Probability</h3>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/data/bayes-theorem/">Bayes' theorem</=
a> describes the probability of an event based on the condition of occurren=
ce of other events. It is also called <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/da=
ta/conditional-probability/">conditional probability</a>. It helps in calcu=
lating the probability of happening of one event based on the condition of =
happening of another event.</p>
<p>For example, let us assume that there are three bags with each bag conta=
ining some blue, green, and yellow balls. What is the probability of pickin=
g a yellow ball from the third bag? Since there are blue and green colored =
balls also, we can arrive at the probability based on these conditions also=
. Such a probability is called conditional probability.</p>
